==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plough
<hw>Plough</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(plou)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>plouh</ets>, <ets>plou</ets>, AS.
<ets>pl⟦omac⟧h</ets>; akin to D. <ets>ploeg</ets>, G. <ets>pflug</ets>,
OHG. <ets>pfluog</ets>, <ets>pfluoh</ets>, Icel. <ets>pl⟦omac⟧gr</ets>,
Sw. <ets>plog</ets>, Dan. <ets>ploug</ets>, <ets>plov</ets>, Russ.
<ets>plug'</ets>, Lith. <ets>plugas</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
well-known implement, drawn by horses, mules, oxen, or other power, for
turning up the soil to prepare it for bearing crops; also used to furrow
or break up the soil for other purposes; <as>as, the subsoil
<ex>plow</ex>; the draining <ex>plow</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where fern succeeds ungrateful to the <qex>plow</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Agriculture; husbandry.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A carucate of land; a plowland.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Johan, mine eldest son, shall have <qex>plowes</qex> five.</q>
<rj><qau>Tale of Gamelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A joiner's plane for making grooves; a grooving
plane.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bookbinding)</fld> <def>An implement for trimming
or shaving off the edges of books.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Charles's
Wain</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ice plow</b></col>, <cd>a plow used for cutting ice on
rivers, ponds, etc.</cd>, into cakes suitable for storing. <mark>[U.
S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Mackerel plow</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Mackerel</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Plow alms</b></col>, <cd>a penny
formerly paid by every plowland to the church.</cd> <au>Cowell.</au> --
<col><b>Plow beam</b></col>, <cd>that part of the frame of a plow to
which the draught is applied. See <er>Beam</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 9.</cd>
-- <col><b>Plow Monday</b></col>, <cd>the Monday after Twelth Day, or
the end of Christmas holidays.</cd> -- <col><b>Plow staff</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A kind of long-handled spade or paddle for cleaning the
plowshare; a paddle staff</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A plow handle.</cd> --
<col><b>Snow plow</b></col>, <cd>a structure, usually ⟦LAMBDA⟧-shaped,
for removing snow from sidewalks, railroads, etc., -- drawn or driven by
a horse or a locomotive.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plough</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Plow</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plough
<hw>Plough</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Plowed</conjf> <pr>(ploud)</pr>
or <conjf>Ploughed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plowing</conjf> or <conjf>Ploughing</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn up, break up, or trench, with a plow; to till
with, or as with, a plow; <as>as, to <ex>plow</ex> the ground; to
<ex>plow</ex> a field.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furrow; to make furrows, grooves, or ridges in;
to run through, as in sailing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let patient Octavia <qex>plow</qex> thy visage up⟦br⟧
With her prepared nails.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With speed we <qex>plow</qex> the watery way.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bookbinding)</fld> <def>To trim, or shave off the
edges of, as a book or paper, with a plow. See <er>Plow</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Joinery)</fld> <def>To cut a groove in, as in a
plank, or the edge of a board; especially, a rectangular groove to
receive the end of a shelf or tread, the edge of a panel, a tongue,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To plow in</b></col>, <cd>to cover by plowing; <as>as,
<ex>to plow in</ex> wheat</as>.</cd><-- ## = plow under --> --
<col><b>To plow up</b></col>, <cd>to turn out of the ground by
plowing.</cd></cs> <-- <col><b>plow ahead</b></col>, <cd>to continue in
spite of obstacles or resistence by others. Often used in a bad sense,
meaning to continue obstinately in spite of the contrary advice of
others.</cd> -- <col><b>plow through</b></col>, <cd>to execute a
difficult or laborious task steadily, esp. one containing many parts;
as, he plowed through the stack of correspondence until all had been
answered.</cd> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plough</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Plow</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Plough
<hw>Plough</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(plou)</pr>, <pos>v.
i.</pos> <def>To labor with, or as with, a plow; to till or turn up the
soil with a plow; to prepare the soil or bed for anything.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Doth the plowman <qex>plow</qex> all day to sow ?</q>
<rj><qau>Isa. xxviii. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ploughable</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Plowable</ent>⟦br⟧
